@merged-from [equity/contribution-pathways equity/contribution-pathways-as-published]
@paper-source /home/joe/npt/paper-v2.3/paper_v2.3.html
@merge-policy Preserve the canonical capability/becoming account while retaining the paper variant's collective-choice principle, steering-group mechanism, contribution log, COM-B signal, and implementation-mode link.

! conclusion: Engagement sustains when trainers become co-producers with recognised scope to shape the programme, not merely recipients or conduits for a central offer. Sustained contribution should create governance standing. Without explicit contribution pathways, delivery becomes goodwill-dependent and the programme benefits from trainer labour without granting voice over the conditions of that labour.
  + context: A programme needs trainers to sustain engagement beyond the first delivery wave. In NPT terms this is Cognitive Participation 2.4 Activation: how procedures and actions that sustain delivery are collectively defined. In Ostrom terms this is the collective-choice problem: can affected participants modify, extend, and help govern the programme, or only consume it? In the paper's tier language this is the first architecture-tier pattern and requires high coordination. In capability terms it is the transition from being shaped by a system to shaping it.
  + IF:
    Trainers have developed local competence through iterative delivery and their adaptations are flowing into the shared commons. The system is learning from variation. But the trainers' relationship to the system may still be one of consumption: they receive the programme, adapt it locally, and upstream improvements, without recognised scope to influence direction, priorities, or structure. Long-term viability rests on moving from receiver to co-producer.
  + HOWEVER:
    There are no explicit pathways for contribution beyond delivery. No peer cohorts, shared adaptation reviews, mentoring structure, steering group, or contribution log exists. The Community of Practice exists but most trainers are unaware of it (T1: "I don't think I was aware of the Community of Practice"). Peer channels exist but go unused (T2B: "in theory, there's a teams channel, but I've never seen anyone use it"). The ORCA coordinator role is undertrained and under-supported (T3: "the ORCAs really didn't get any training"; FG3: "reactive rather than helpful"). Where co-ownership emerged, sustained motivation followed (FG1.19, FG1.25; T1: "That ownership felt really important to me"). Where it did not, engagement remained precarious and vulnerable to the trainer leaving (FG3.11; T3: "At some point I potentially leave with that knowledge and it doesn't get used as much as it could have"). COM-B shows a value/activation gap: "I see the value" M=5.37 vs. "I feel positive" M=4.21.
  + THEN:
    The programme builds governed community infrastructure: a steering group drawn from active contributors, a contribution log that makes otherwise-invisible labour visible in career-relevant terms, actively stewarded peer channels, mentoring structures, adaptation reviews, and a properly resourced coordinator role. Sustained contribution creates recognised standing in programme governance. Governance standing follows meaningful contribution, not the other way around. Shared investment in community infrastructure presupposes capability return: participants invest because the investment enlarges their real ability to contribute and benefit.
  + BECAUSE:
    NPT: Activation is the collective definition of the actions and procedures that sustain a practice. Without contribution pathways, only the central programme has standing to define; activation stays private.

    Sen: Capability expands when participants move from receipt to co-ownership. The deepest capability expansion is not skill acquisition, but the freedom to revise the conditions under which action takes place.

    Whole-board play: This is the transition from playing within a fixed architecture to modifying the architecture itself. A distribution list delivers content; a community of practice co-evolves content, delivery, and governance.

    Ostrom: Collective-choice arrangements give those who sustain the commons recognised rights to shape it. A programme that benefits from trainer labour without granting governance voice is extractive by structure, regardless of stated intentions.

    Convergence with visible impact: contribution pathways and visible impact share architecture. Trainers who contribute to design also need to see their effects to remain contributors.
  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Establish a steering group drawn from active contributors
    - Build a contribution log that makes invisible labour visible in career-relevant terms
    - Resource and train the coordinator role before expecting community to emerge
    - Actively steward peer channels: facilitation, not just creation
    - Define explicit contribution pathways: adaptation review, mentoring, programme governance
    - Design governance so sustained contribution creates recognised standing
    - Test: does a motivated trainer have a visible route into co-ownership within the first year?
  + INVARIANT-STATEMENT:
    Every participant who sustains engagement beyond initial training has at least one visible route to contribute to programme development, governance, or community support. Sustained contribution creates recognised standing. The coordinator role is resourced and trained.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Capped becoming: agent develops local competence but cannot reshape the system
    - Goodwill-dependent delivery: practice survives only as long as the individual persists
    - Invisible community: CoP exists formally but trainers are unaware
    - Dead channels: peer exchange channels are created but unstewarded and unused
    - Undertrained coordinators: ORCA role exists but is reactive rather than helpful
    - Knowledge exit: trainers leave with knowledge the programme fails to retain
    - Extractive structure: system benefits from trainer labour without granting governance voice
    - Value/activation gap: value is recognised but positive activation remains weak
  + ANCESTORS:
    - Paper v2.3, Pattern 4: Contribution Pathways
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T1 ("That ownership felt really important to me")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T1 ("I wouldn't have delivered that training if I hadn't had this framework")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T3 ("At some point I potentially leave with that knowledge")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T1 ("I don't think I was aware of the Community of Practice")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T2B ("in theory, there's a teams channel, but I've never seen anyone use it")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T3 ("the ORCAs really didn't get any training")
    - Focus-group codes: FG1.19, FG1.25 (co-ownership -> sustained motivation); FG3.11 (precarious engagement)
    - COM-B: "I see the value" M=5.37 vs. "I feel positive" M=4.21
    - Ostrom (1990): collective-choice principle
  + DERIVATION:
    Derived from NPT Cognitive Participation 2.4 Activation.
    Tier: Architecture. Coordination: High (governed infrastructure).
    Implementation-mode link: this pattern separates absorbed input from multiplied input.
    Canonical deepening: capability as the freedom to revise programme conditions.
    Paper-specific mechanism: steering group, contribution log, and governance-follows-contribution.
